         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">12/3/94. ¶  ¶ Am always delighted, dear Mr Tyson, when a parcel of plants arrives from you, as it always contains some of prominent interest. ¶  ¶ After so dry a season, the change of a wet one is inc...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">95.03.12</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Isaac Tyson</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">MS 58 (044) MUE, WA Herbarium, Perth.</seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS black-edged.</p>
               </note>12/3/94.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Am always delighted, dear Mr Tyson, when a parcel of plants arrives from you, as it always contains some of prominent interest.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>After so dry a season, the change of a wet one is increased. May turn out a glorious year for you and your kind brothers</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I will send a large parcel of fresh seeds of economic plants by next mail. They will arrive probably at the best season for sowing.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Do any of the <name key="Acacia">Acacia</name>s there bear gum in appreciable quantity?</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>What you say about the Beet having grown where Peas and Beans seem to fail, is most interesting you may thus gain an important kitchen- and stable-plant.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Such notes will always be welcome indeed, as we know so little as yet about the cultural capabilities of the Murray Regions.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">WA, south of Perth on the western slopes of the Darling escarpment. There is a small amount of evidence that the Tyson brothers had interests or connections in the area, but this has not been confirmed.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Will soon write again.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Wish you all every happiness and success</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">The Murchison Goldfield journal<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Murchison times and "day dawn gazette"</seg> (Cue, WA) began publication in August 1894 and is probably the 'journal' mentioned here. No account by Tyson of his 'Beet &amp;c' has been found in that newspaper, but Tyson's interest in fodder plants is illustrated by a small item in the issue of 5 August 1897, p. 2, which reports that he sent several varieties of seed to the Secretary of the WA Bureau of Agriculture.</p>
               </note> would be sure to be glad of notes on your Beet &amp;c</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Acacia">Acacia</name>
            </p>
